  <h1>Methodology &mdash; How We Estimate Burn Injury Compensation</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by our editorial team. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>This page documents how the calculator on the homepage arrives at a recovery range. The estimate is built from published burn-case settlement data, the life-care planning frameworks used in catastrophic injury litigation, and the structured damages categories that govern burn practice. Burn cases differ from generic personal-injury cases in two important ways: the future-medical-care component is unusually long-tailed (reconstructive surgery is iterative over years, sometimes decades), and disfigurement damages are often treated as a separate category with its own valuation logic.</p>

  <h2>Damages framework: six components</h2>

  <p>A burn-injury case typically claims damages in six categories. Each has its own valuation logic.</p>

  <h3>1. Past medical expenses</h3>

  <p>Documented costs from the date of injury through trial or settlement. For a burn case, this typically includes:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Emergency response and field stabilization</strong> &mdash; ambulance or helicopter transport to a verified burn center; many regions have only one or two burn centers, and pre-hospital transport distance is non-trivial.</li>
    <li><strong>Acute burn-center admission</strong> &mdash; ICU-level care, escharotomies, fasciotomies, surgical debridement, repeated dressing changes (often under anesthesia), nutritional support, infection management. $200K&ndash;$2M+ for severe burns; even moderate burns commonly run $50K&ndash;$200K.</li>
    <li><strong>Skin grafting</strong> &mdash; split-thickness autografts are typical for full-thickness burns; cultured epidermal autografts (CEA) and allografts in extensive burns. Multiple operative sessions are common.</li>
    <li><strong>Inpatient rehabilitation</strong> &mdash; positioning, splinting, range-of-motion, scar-management initiation. Often runs 2&ndash;8 weeks following acute discharge.</li>
    <li><strong>Outpatient care</strong> &mdash; ongoing wound care, dressing supplies, pressure-garment fittings, occupational and physical therapy.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Past medical expenses are typically claimed at billed amounts in most states and at paid amounts in others, depending on the collateral source rule.</p>

  <h3>2. Future medical expenses</h3>

  <p>For severe burns this is the largest single component. A certified life care planner (CLCP), often with burn-specific experience, itemizes projected costs through expected lifespan. Categories typically include:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Reconstructive surgery.</strong> Severe burn survivors typically undergo dozens of reconstructive procedures over years &mdash; scar revision, Z-plasty, contracture release, tissue expansion, free-flap reconstruction. $30K&ndash;$80K per procedure; multiple per year for several years post-injury.</li>
    <li><strong>Hypertrophic scar treatment.</strong> Intralesional steroid injections, fractional laser therapy, silicone sheeting, and pressure-garment maintenance. $5K&ndash;$20K/year recurring for the first 2&ndash;5 years.</li>
    <li><strong>Pressure garments.</strong> Custom-fit garments worn 23 hours/day for 12&ndash;24 months in severe cases; replaced every 2&ndash;3 months. $3K&ndash;$10K/year.</li>
    <li><strong>Therapy.</strong> Occupational and physical therapy for hand burns, contracture management, and overall function. Often years of recurring therapy.</li>
    <li><strong>Psychiatric care.</strong> Treatment for PTSD, depression, body-image disorders, and burn-related anxiety. Burn-survivor literature documents high rates of long-term psychiatric sequelae.</li>
    <li><strong>Skin care, sun protection, and recurrent wound care.</strong> Grafted skin is permanently more fragile, requires lifetime SPF management, and is at higher risk of skin cancer.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Future medical care for severe burns (25%+ TBSA, full-thickness involvement, face/hand burns) commonly produces present-value totals of $500K&ndash;$3M+.</p>

  <h3>3. Lost earnings (past and future)</h3>

  <p>Components:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Past lost wages from injury to trial.</li>
    <li>Future lost earning capacity: pre-injury career trajectory minus realistic post-burn residual earning capacity. Hand and face burns reduce capacity across most occupations; even modest TBSA burns can sideline workers in trades, food service, and customer-facing roles.</li>
    <li>Lost benefits: employer-paid health insurance, retirement contributions, life insurance.</li>
    <li>Household services: replacement value of cooking, childcare, yard work the injured person can no longer perform.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>For a 35-year-old earning $60K/year with severe upper-body and hand burns, lost-earnings present value commonly falls in the $600K&ndash;$1.5M range.</p>

  <h3>4. Pain and suffering (non-economic damages)</h3>

  <p>Burn-injury pain-and-suffering valuations are higher than for most other injury types of comparable economic severity. The justification, supported by both the medical and legal literature, is that:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>The acute treatment course is exceptionally painful (dressing changes, debridement, harvest sites for grafting).</li>
    <li>The treatment is prolonged, often months in the burn center followed by years of outpatient care.</li>
    <li>Reconstructive surgery, while elective, is itself painful and emotionally taxing.</li>
    <li>PTSD rates in burn survivors are among the highest documented in any injury category.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Typical multipliers for catastrophic burns range from 3x to 6x economic damages, somewhat higher than the 2x&ndash;5x range typical of other catastrophic injuries.</p>

  <h3>5. Disfigurement damages</h3>

  <p>Most jurisdictions allow disfigurement as a separate damages category, distinct from general pain-and-suffering. Disfigurement valuation depends on:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Visibility.</strong> Face, neck, and hands command the largest disfigurement awards. Trunk burns under typical clothing produce smaller but still meaningful awards.</li>
    <li><strong>Severity.</strong> Mature hypertrophic scarring, contractures distorting normal contour, depigmentation in grafted skin.</li>
    <li><strong>Age and life expectancy.</strong> Younger claimants face longer lives with the disfigurement; awards scale with remaining life expectancy.</li>
    <li><strong>Occupation.</strong> Claimants in customer-facing or performance occupations argue (and often establish) larger disfigurement impact.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Disfigurement awards in moderate-to-severe burn cases commonly fall $200K&ndash;$2M+, depending on the above factors.</p>

  <h3>6. Loss of consortium and family damages</h3>

  <p>Available in most states for the spouse and (in some states) for parents and children. In burn cases, loss of consortium often emphasizes the intimacy and physical-contact impact of significant burns, particularly when genital, perineal, or breast involvement is present. Adds $250K&ndash;$2M+ in significant cases.</p>

  <h2>Modifier: cause and liability source</h2>

  <p>The calculator's "cause" field is a proxy for both the typical liability framework and the typical insurance source:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Defective product</strong> (lithium-battery fires, e-cigarette explosions, defective gas grills, faulty appliances) &mdash; commercial defendants with substantial coverage; clear failure-mode evidence. Highest multiplier.</li>
    <li><strong>Electrical and high-voltage</strong> &mdash; often industrial/utility defendants with high coverage limits; OSHA documentation supports liability.</li>
    <li><strong>Fire</strong> (house fires, vehicle fires) &mdash; landlord liability for smoke detectors and fire-code violations; vehicle product liability claims. Moderate-to-high multiplier.</li>
    <li><strong>Chemical</strong> (acid, alkali, hydrofluoric) &mdash; industrial or product-liability defendants; OSHA and EPA records support liability.</li>
    <li><strong>Scald</strong> (restaurants, workplace, daycare) &mdash; well-developed premises and workplace liability framework; coverage limits often modest.</li>
    <li><strong>Friction and contact</strong> &mdash; varied; often workplace or premises with mixed liability.</li>
    <li><strong>Radiation</strong> &mdash; medical and dental defendants (UV exposure, radiation therapy, sun-tanning); standard professional liability coverage.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Modifier: jurisdiction</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>California, New York, Pennsylvania, Illinois (Cook County), New Jersey:</strong> well-developed burn-injury practice, no general damages caps, plaintiff-friendly juries. Median recoveries often 10&ndash;20% above national average.</li>
    <li><strong>Florida, Massachusetts, Maryland, Connecticut:</strong> standard plaintiff jurisdictions; recoveries near national average.</li>
    <li><strong>Texas, Georgia, some Southern states:</strong> generally less plaintiff-friendly, various damages caps in product liability or med-mal, more conservative juries; recoveries below national average for similar cases.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Worked example</h2>

  <p>Consider a 32-year-old with 35% TBSA 2nd-to-3rd degree burns including bilateral hand involvement, caused by a defective lithium-battery e-cigarette explosion in California, pre-injury income of $70K:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Past medical expenses (burn-center admission, grafting, rehab to date): ~$650K.</li>
    <li>Future medical care (reconstructive surgery, scar treatment, hand therapy, psychiatric care, PV): ~$1.1M.</li>
    <li>Lost earnings (PV; manual dexterity-dependent work): ~$900K.</li>
    <li>Pain and suffering (4x multiplier on economic damages): ~$10.6M nominal.</li>
    <li>Disfigurement (visible hand scarring, mature hypertrophic scars): ~$600K.</li>
    <li>Loss of consortium for spouse: ~$300K.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Total nominal claim: ~$14.2M. Practical settlement constrained by defendant product-liability coverage; typical resolution in the $3M&ndash;$7M range for a case of this profile.</p>

  <h2>What the calculator does NOT include</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Punitive damages</strong> &mdash; available in cases of gross negligence (e.g., manufacturer concealment of known fire risk, repeat fire-code violations by a landlord). Punitive awards can substantially exceed compensatory damages but are case-specific.</li>
    <li><strong>Bad-faith insurance claims</strong> &mdash; available in some states when the insurer unreasonably refuses to settle within policy limits.</li>
    <li><strong>Specific structured-settlement arrangements</strong> &mdash; the choice between lump sum and periodic payments affects long-term economics.</li>
    <li><strong>Public benefits</strong> &mdash; SSDI, Medicaid, and state burn-survivor support programs operate independently of civil litigation; coordination matters for the family's planning.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Honest about uncertainty</h2>

  <p>Burn-injury case valuations vary widely based on factors a calculator cannot capture: defendant insurance availability, liability disputes, jurisdiction-specific procedural rules, the specific burn course (graft success vs. graft loss, sepsis vs. uncomplicated course, hypertrophic vs. flat scarring), and family circumstances. The calculator's range is a starting reference, not a prediction. An experienced burn-injury attorney can provide much more specific valuation after reviewing the actual records.</p>

